00:01:45.420 --> 00:01:47.660
It's the projects.

00:01:47.660 --> 00:01:48.960
So there were 5 of us.

00:01:48.960 --> 00:01:53.150
I'm the eldest of 5 and my mom
and dad in a 2 bedroom apartment.

00:01:53.150 --> 00:01:55.120
So you can imagine.

00:01:55.120 --> 00:01:58.440
But my father's thing was
education, with education

00:01:58.440 --> 00:02:02.310
and determination you can do
anything in the world you want.

00:02:02.310 --> 00:02:06.890
So he spent all, he and mommy,
spent their money on educating us,

00:02:06.890 --> 00:02:08.860
putting us through
parochial schools,

00:02:08.860 --> 00:02:11.450
all kind of private
schools, dance classes,

00:02:11.450 --> 00:02:14.690
you know music classes,
and things like that.

00:02:14.690 --> 00:02:18.720 position:56%
And you know I can remember going to
school, it was like 10 blocks away

00:02:18.720 --> 00:02:20.810
from you know where we lived.

00:02:20.810 --> 00:02:24.690
And it was called Our Lady of
Loreto and on the way there,

00:02:24.690 --> 00:02:28.930
I learned a lot of things, about
the neighborhood, about life.

00:02:28.930 --> 00:02:33.440
And what we would see all the
time would be the heroin addicts,

00:02:33.440 --> 00:02:36.350
you know, going, when
I was going to school,

00:02:36.350 --> 00:02:39.550 position:56%
now you know what heroin addicts do.

00:02:39.550 --> 00:02:42.190
And the hands on the
heroin addicts were

00:02:42.190 --> 00:02:44.810
like three times the
size that they should be.

00:02:44.810 --> 00:02:51.160
And what we would do is, as
children we would make bets as to

00:02:51.160 --> 00:02:55.830 position:56%
which one would fall, you know which
one would hit the ground first.

00:02:55.830 --> 00:02:59.190
And as you know, they never fall.

00:02:59.190 --> 00:03:00.490
&gt;&gt; That's right.

00:03:00.490 --> 00:03:01.790
&gt;&gt; Bern Nadette Stanis:
It was amazing.

00:03:01.790 --> 00:03:04.340
They would go all the
way down to the ground

00:03:04.340 --> 00:03:05.640
and never fall [laughter].

00:03:05.640 --> 00:03:07.670
We just thought that was amazing.

00:03:07.670 --> 00:03:11.980 position:56%
So I'm just saying that this was
the kind of environment I came from.

00:03:11.980 --> 00:03:14.980
And what my father
always said was this,

00:03:14.980 --> 00:03:16.990
what's around you does
not have to be in you.

00:03:16.990 --> 00:03:22.080
And he made sure that
we understood that.

00:03:22.080 --> 00:03:25.630
He was a very wonderful daddy,
he was a very disciplinarian,

00:03:25.630 --> 00:03:30.090
he was very strong in that way at
education and being disciplined.

00:03:30.090 --> 00:03:33.930
Mother, on the other
hand, a southern gal,

00:03:33.930 --> 00:03:36.800
you know from Jeanerette,
Louisiana, she was very,

00:03:36.800 --> 00:03:39.670
very soft spoken but
very, very stern.

00:03:39.670 --> 00:03:41.740
And she meant what she said.

00:03:41.740 --> 00:03:45.050
Some of the lessons that I learned
from them, I'll just jump ahead.

00:03:45.050 --> 00:03:50.290
My grandmother put me in dance
class at the age of 5 years old

00:03:50.290 --> 00:03:53.280
and told my mother
to keep me in dance.

00:03:53.280 --> 00:03:55.230
And I think she did
that because she knew

00:03:55.230 --> 00:03:59.710
that if you were busy doing
something positive there's less

00:03:59.710 --> 00:04:02.570
opportunity to get into
something negative.

00:04:02.570 --> 00:04:07.790
So I stayed in dance class all
of my life to become a dancer.

00:04:07.790 --> 00:04:14.900 position:56%
Now, I remember a lesson, one of the
lessons that I learned, from my mom.

00:04:14.900 --> 00:04:17.260
I was about in the tenth grade,

00:04:17.260 --> 00:04:20.620
no I was about in the fifth
grade and I was 10 years old.

00:04:20.620 --> 00:04:25.350
And there were two girls in my
class that I wanted to be a part

00:04:25.350 --> 00:04:28.540
of their clique, that's when
I learned about cliques.

00:04:28.540 --> 00:04:33.040
And [laughter] I wanted to
be a part of them so badly

00:04:33.040 --> 00:04:36.740
because they were beautiful,
they were smart,

00:04:36.740 --> 00:04:39.670 position:56%
they were everything I wanted to be.

00:04:39.670 --> 00:04:43.700
I was the type of student
that, I was very creative

00:04:43.700 --> 00:04:47.370
but I was like a B, C student.

00:04:47.370 --> 00:04:50.280
So they didn't want
me in their clique.

00:04:50.280 --> 00:04:53.450
I figured this out from the
first grade to the fifth grade.

00:04:53.450 --> 00:04:58.940
Now what I figured out was this,
if I can become an A student

00:04:58.940 --> 00:05:02.440
like they were, then I would
automatically you know,

00:05:02.440 --> 00:05:04.700
be part of their clique.

00:05:04.700 --> 00:05:08.060
So I studied and I
became an A student.

00:05:08.060 --> 00:05:10.280
This one test was very,
very hard and I got an A

00:05:10.280 --> 00:05:12.430
and I was so excited, so happy.

00:05:12.430 --> 00:05:16.280
So in recess here I am, you know
they're playing double Dutch,

00:05:16.280 --> 00:05:18.230
you all know about
double Dutch [laughter].

00:05:18.230 --> 00:05:24.250
And I am walking over to them
and say okay, can I play?

00:05:24.250 --> 00:05:30.580
And they looked at me like they
always looked at me and said no.

00:05:30.580 --> 00:05:32.020
No you can't play.

00:05:32.020 --> 00:05:35.430
Well that was a lesson
that, that I'll never forget

00:05:35.430 --> 00:05:37.760
because it really, really hurt me.

00:05:37.760 --> 00:05:41.230
I did not understand that, I didn't
understand why I was not accepted,

00:05:41.230 --> 00:05:42.810
why they didn't like me.

00:05:42.810 --> 00:05:47.300
So again I go home that day crying,
you know, asking my mommy, why,

00:05:47.300 --> 00:05:49.630 position:56%
why don't they accept me mommy, why?

00:05:49.630 --> 00:05:53.840
And she says, I don't know why
Bern Nadette, I really don't.

00:05:53.840 --> 00:05:57.860
She said but listen, you are
very creative, you can dance,

00:05:57.860 --> 00:06:01.440
you can draw, you can
paint, you can write.

00:06:01.440 --> 00:06:05.290
I'm like ugh, that's not
what a child wants to hear

00:06:05.290 --> 00:06:08.340 position:56%
in a situation like that [laughter].

00:06:08.340 --> 00:06:11.880
So I moped around and I moped
around that whole evening.

00:06:11.880 --> 00:06:17.980
And I, I'm very religious and
I believe in God very strongly

00:06:17.980 --> 00:06:21.490
and I think that is
because my mom did too.

00:06:21.490 --> 00:06:26.480
And sometimes I believe that,
we get messages from God

00:06:26.480 --> 00:06:29.250
to help us guide our children.

00:06:29.250 --> 00:06:33.920
And I know that this had to have
happened for my mother, this day.

00:06:33.920 --> 00:06:37.260
So she came in the living room
and she sat right next to me

00:06:37.260 --> 00:06:40.410
and she said, Bern Nadette,

00:06:40.410 --> 00:06:45.650
one day the whole world is
going to know your name.

00:06:45.650 --> 00:06:48.970
Yet she didn't tell me that Thelma
would be the first name [laughter]

00:06:50.360 --> 00:06:56.670
instead of Bern Nadette, she didn't
tell me that part [laughter].

00:06:56.670 --> 00:06:59.850
So, so I said okay mom,
whatever, but that,

00:06:59.850 --> 00:07:02.580
but you know the clique thing
faded away and I continued on

00:07:02.580 --> 00:07:04.750
and to do what I, you know do.

00:07:04.750 --> 00:07:06.960
Another lesson was this.

00:07:06.960 --> 00:07:09.990
I learned a lot about my
mother's character from this.

00:07:09.990 --> 00:07:14.170
There was a beauty
pageant, and I wanted to be

00:07:14.170 --> 00:07:16.340
in it but I was too young.

00:07:16.340 --> 00:07:23.330
The pageant, Miss Black America
was from 18 on and I was about 14.

00:07:23.330 --> 00:07:29.110
And my mother said, you know there
should be a pageant for teenagers,

00:07:29.110 --> 00:07:31.520
they want to get in
these things too.

00:07:31.520 --> 00:07:35.810
So of course, being the mother
that she was, she went to the head

00:07:35.810 --> 00:07:38.380
of the pageant you know thing.

00:07:38.380 --> 00:07:42.280
And Mr. Hal Jackson
was the leader then.

00:07:42.280 --> 00:07:47.620 position:56%
And she went over to him and she
said, Mr. Jackson, my daughter is 14

00:07:47.620 --> 00:07:50.880
and I know a lot of teenagers
want to get into pageants

00:07:50.880 --> 00:07:53.260
so why don't you have
a teenage pageant?

00:07:53.260 --> 00:07:57.120
The very next year he
had that teenage pageant.

00:07:57.120 --> 00:08:01.200
So, well what I learned
from that was

00:08:01.200 --> 00:08:04.360
that when there is no
way you can make a way,

00:08:04.360 --> 00:08:07.820
if there's no door you can
make a door to walk through.

00:08:07.820 --> 00:08:10.020 position:56%
And my mother made that door for me.

00:08:10.020 --> 00:08:14.980
Now, I am going to the beauty
pageant every Sunday with my mother

00:08:14.980 --> 00:08:18.730
and her other four children,
so, all the way to Manhattan,

00:08:18.730 --> 00:08:21.880
so it takes about, about
an hour to get there.

00:08:21.880 --> 00:08:24.720
We did this for about 6 weeks

00:08:24.720 --> 00:08:27.380
and the seventh week was
the pageant, that Sunday.

00:08:27.380 --> 00:08:35.300
And I got up that morning and I
looked in the mirror, and I said,

00:08:35.300 --> 00:08:39.320
I am not going to that
pageant [laughter].

00:08:39.320 --> 00:08:45.860
Not me, I meant that to, so I moped
around, I looked kind of strange.

00:08:45.860 --> 00:08:48.290
And my mother says you
better start getting dressed,

00:08:48.290 --> 00:08:49.750
